      <h2 class="!text-xl mb-6">Frequently asked questions</h2>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-2">Does Perplexity send traffic to my website?</h3>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-8">Yes. Perplexity includes clickable source citations in every answer. Users regularly click through to read the full source. This makes Perplexity the AI platform most likely to drive real referral traffic to your site.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-2">How does Perplexity decide which sources to cite?</h3>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-8">Perplexity looks for relevance (does the page answer the question), authority (is the source trustworthy), freshness (is the content recent), and clarity (can it extract a clean answer). Pages that score well across all four factors get cited most consistently.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-2">Is Perplexity the same as ChatGPT?</h3>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-8">No. Perplexity crawls the web in real-time and always shows its sources. ChatGPT relies more on training data and does not consistently cite sources. The two platforms require different optimisation approaches.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-2">How quickly can I appear on Perplexity?</h3>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-8">Because Perplexity crawls in real-time, a new well-structured page can appear as a citation within days of publication. This is significantly faster than ChatGPT or Gemini, where new content may take weeks or months to surface.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-2">Does Perplexity use my Google ranking?</h3>
      <p class="text-[17px] text-text-muted leading-relaxed mb-8">Perplexity has its own crawling and ranking system. Google ranking helps indirectly because high-authority pages tend to be cited more, but Perplexity makes its own decisions. A page ranking on page two of Google can still be cited as source number one on Perplexity if it has the best answer.</p>
